metadata.label: title
metadata.value: [Betsy Reed et al. case testimonies]: Department of the Interior, Commission to the Five Civilized Tribes, Vinita, I. T., October 26th, 1901

metadata.label: abstract
metadata.value: Testimony of Betsy Reed a former enslaved African American, for the enrollment of herself and her five grandchildren (Silas Harris, Mamie Harris, Hannah Brown,  Myrtle Brown, Mima Harris) as Cherokee Freedmen. The testimonies of Sam Webber, Harry Still, John H. Coody and Henry Armstrong are also included. Betsy testifies that she was formerly enslaved by "Aleck McPherson," a Cherokee citizen, who lived on "Dog Creek" in the Cherokee Nation. She moved to Mound City, Kansas during the Civil War. She testifies that she has lived off and on in Mound City since the war ended, and has returned to the Cherokee Nation several times. Sam Webber and Harry Still testify that they saw her near Coody's Bluff in the Cherokee Nation in 1866. and that she returned to the Cherokee Nation again during the Wallace roll. Meanwhile, Betsy could not be identified in any of the Cherokee tribal rolls except for the Kern-Clifton roll. It is decided that Betsy and her grandchildren are to be placed on a "doubtful card" for further consideration by the Commission.
